  "prompt": "What do police officers do when they retire from active duty?",
  "response": "When police officers retire, they have several potential paths:\n\n1. Security work\n- Private security jobs\n- Corporate security positions\n- Campus or event security\n- Loss prevention roles\n\n2. Related law enforcement careers\n- Private investigator\n- Criminal justice instructor\n- Consultant for law enforcement agencies\n- Court bailiff\n- Probation or parole officer\n\n3. Training and education\n- Police academy instructor\n- Teach criminal justice at colleges\n- Training and development roles\n- Provide expert testimony in legal cases\n\n4. Government positions\n- Emergency management\n- Homeland security\n- Government administrative roles\n- Community safety coordinator\n\n5. Civilian jobs\n- Real estate\n- Insurance investigations\n- Risk management\n- Sales or customer service\n\n6. Pursue personal interests\n- Start a business\n- Volunteer work\n- Spend time with family\n- Travel\n- Pursue hobbies\n\n7. Pension and benefits\n- Collect retirement pension\n- Maintain health insurance benefits\n- Some continue part-time work to supplement income\n\nMany retired officers leverage their law enforcement experience and skills in various professional settings, often staying connected to public service or security-related fields.",
